title: Overscan 1° beyond the ends of the level arc to correctly handle extreme marker locations
message:
Overscan 1° beyond the ends of the level arc to correctly handle extreme marker locations

At level 1, and at (playerLevel+2), the marker hangs off the ends of the
level arc.
With the new averaging algorithm, this was causing failed detection of
Pokemon at (playerLevel+2). Such high levels aren't normally reachable
in the game, but they can/could be reached by exploiting glitches.

This issue doesn't show up for level 1 Pokemon because the jump from
level 1 to 1.5 on the arc is so massive.

title: Rewrite the level arc reading code
message:
Rewrite the level arc reading code

The new strategy is as follows:
- Check at the given angle, slightly above the arc. If not white, reject
the angle.
- Check at the given angle, slightly below the arc. If not white, reject
the angle.
- Check too far above and below the arc. If either is white, reject the
angle. (This is so that we don't mistake the gym/buddy overlay for a
level marker.)
- Finally, check the angle on the arc. If it's not white, the arc is
likely covered there, so reject the angle. Otherwise, accept the angle
as a candidate.

Once all candidate angles have been collected, find the highest
candidate, and return the average of all candidates no more than 2
degrees below the highest one. We can't just average across all
candidates, as things overlapping the level arc will cause false
positives (I'm looking at you, Gyarados...) 2 degrees were chosen as an
upper bound for the angle subtended by the level marker on the arc.

title: 180° corresponds to player+2, not player+1.5

180° corresponds to player+2, not player+1.5

title: Parse level arc with 0.1° accuracy (up from 1°)
message:
Parse level arc with 0.1° accuracy (up from 1°)

Above level 31, adjacent half-levels can round to the same whole degree.
As a result, 1° precision is insufficient to distinguish between these
levels.

Increase precision to 0.1° when reading the level arc.

title: Render dummy icon for Pokemon missing from icon set
message:
Render dummy icon for Pokemon missing from icon set

The dummy icon is taken from the bottom right corner of the icon set
image.

The best way to take advantage of this is to fill all empty slots in the
last row
of the image with copies of the dummy icon (e.g. a question mark), or
if no empty slots, add a new row of dummy icons.
